This code solves the "01 Matrix" problem, which finds the distance of each cell to the nearest 0 in a binary matrix.
\It uses a multi-source BFS approach: all cells containing 0 are initially added to the queue with distance 0, while cells with 1 are marked as -1 (unvisited). 
Then BFS propagates outward level by level, updating the distance for each 1 cell as dist[row][col] + 1 when first visited, ensuring each cell gets the shortest distance to any 0. 
The BFS guarantees optimal distances because all 0 sources expand simultaneously. Finally, the distance matrix is returned.

Time Complexity: O(m × n) - each cell is processed once.
Space Complexity: O(m × n) - for the distance matrix and the queue (which can hold up to m×n cells in worst case).


import java.util.*;
class Solution{
    public int[][] updateMatrix(int[][] mat) {
        int m = mat.length;
        int n = mat[0].length;
        int[][] dist = new int[m][n];
        Queue<int[]> q = new LinkedList<>();
        for(int i = 0; i<m; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j<n; j++){
                if(mat[i][j] == 0){
                    q.offer(new int[]{i, j});
                } else{
                    dist[i][j] = -1;
                }
            }
        }
        int[][] directions = {{-1,0}, {1,0}, {0,-1}, {0,1}};
        while(!q.isEmpty()){
            int[] curr = q.poll();
            int row = curr[0];
            int col = curr[1];
            for(int[] dir: directions){
                int newRow = row + dir[0];
                int newCol = col + dir[1];
                if(newRow >= 0 && newRow < m && newCol >= 0 && newCol < n && dist[newRow][newCol] == -1){
                    dist[newRow][newCol] = dist[row][col] + 1;
                    q.offer(new int[]{newRow, newCol});
                }
            }
        }
        return dist;
    }
}

